Once you accept the sad truth that you&#39;ll need to maintain some runtime artifact related to `V`, since `V` itself will be [erased](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/FAQ#what-is-type-erasure), and assuming you can&#39;t actually use the runtime artifact to *define* `V`, the best you can do is have the compiler yell at you if your runtime artifact and `V` are out of sync.  Here&#39;s one way to do it:

    interface V {
        a: number;
        b: string;
    }

    const keysOfV = [&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;] as const;
    type MutuallyAssignable&lt;T extends U, U extends V, V = T&gt; = void;
    // the following line will give an error if keysOfV is wrong
    type KeysOfVIsGood = MutuallyAssignable&lt;keyof V, typeof keysOfV[number]&gt;; // okay

