The beautiful of Cloudinary is to be able to upload the originals and then apply a transformation. Typically the recommendation looks to be: 

 1. Set `quality` parameter as `auto` (**q_auto** in URLs) to automatically adjust the quality of the image for the right balance between quality and size
 2. Set `fetch_format` parameter as `auto` (**f_auto** in URLs) to automatically choose the best format depending on the browser.
 3. Adjusting the height and width to necessary dimensions being rendered on the page.

Example: https://res.cloudinary.com/demo/image/upload/q_auto,f_auto,w_500/bike.jpg

**Source (and more info)**: https://cloudinary.com/documentation/image_optimization).

But if you need to re-upload the content and keep the same `public_id`, the easiest solution would be to use their APIs. I would suggest doing the following:

 1. Retrieve the assets that need to be re-uploaded using the [Admin APIs get resources call](https://cloudinary.com/documentation/admin_api#get_resources). I would suggest breaking these down by `resource_type` and I would also include the parameters `tags` set as `true` and `context` set as `true` if being used. **Note** The Admin API is rate limited so check what usage limit is associated to your plan [here](https://cloudinary.com/documentation/admin_api#usage_limits). Store these in an array for use later. The response should include `public_id`, `url`, `tags`, `context`, etc...
 2. Iterate over the previous array and use the [Upload API&#39;s upload method](https://cloudinary.com/documentation/image_upload_api_reference#upload_method) to re-upload the content using the same parameters retrieved earlier (`public_id`, `url`, `tags`, `context`, etc.. e.g. 

        current_assets = [...]
        for (asset in current_assets) {
            result = cloudinary.v2.uploader.upload(
                asset[&#39;url&#39;], 
                { public_id: asset[&#39;public_id&#39;], tags: asset[&#39;tags&#39;], context: assets[&#39;context&#39;]
                // include any incoming transformations to apply to the asset during upload
                },
                (err, res) =&gt; {
                    if (err) console.log(err);
                console.log(res);
            })
        }

**Source**: https://cloudinary.com/documentation/upload_images?query=incoming&amp;c_query=Incoming%20transformations#incoming_transformations

